<br>
Now...  let me begin... *clears throat*<br>
<br>
The Church of Satan is setup more as a moral code than any kind of actual religion per se...  at least initially.  They live more by the concepts of immediate gratification and self-satisfaction than by the denial of the natural human urges that all of us feel.  The reason for the use of the name Satan (in so far as this has been explained to me anyway at various discussion groups) was initally for the shock value.  What better way than to announce a philosophy that was so diametrically opposed to all of the major western religions than to invoke the name of the key figure signifying evil than by using the name of Satan?  <br>
<br>
As time went on, however, La Vey realized that without a little more to work with, his philosophy would not live up to the truly wicked sounding name he had chosen.  With that in mind, he simply delved deep into various religious texts, digging up names of fallen angels and other such demons, which he inevitably mixed in with a healthy dose of pagan ritual.  These &quot;rites&quot; to &quot;summon the very princes of Hell&quot; to aid the satanist were nothing more than meaningless words written down to make people feel that they were receiving the energy to do what they weren't confident enough in themselves to do without them.<br>
<br>
Now...  I understand that this is just a dry history of the creation of the Church of Satan (again, as it was explained to me at various discussion groups [also, it should be noted that it was explained to me by persons who have left the &quot;church&quot; because of the hypocracy inherent in any massed religious group]).  However, what I personally do not understand is how it is that a group of people who simply want to live by the philosophy of &quot;Do as thou will&quot; are so greatly feared and despised by groups that are supposed to pride themselves on acceptance and forgiveness (i.e. Love the sinner, hate the sin).<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8o --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/nerd.gif ALT="8o"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>You know what they say...  rub the Tummy and you'll have good luck all day...</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mormongirl2>Mormongirl2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 226<br> <font color=#3333ff>(4/14/03 11:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=187.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Satanism</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>However, what I personally do not understand is how it is that a group of people who simply want to live by the philosophy of &quot;Do as thou will&quot; are so greatly feared and despised by groups that are supposed to pride themselves on acceptance and forgiveness (i.e. Love the sinner, hate the sin<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Satan, the person, is a coniving individual, whose whole goal is to lead people away from the gospel of Christ and his doctrines of loving your neighbor, self control over your passions and personal salvation.    <br>
<br>
If he can do that by convincing these people (who invoke his name without actually believing in him) that life is all about self indulgence and seeking after all your lusts with no regard for anyone else, well then he has put chains around those souls and is carefully leading them down to hell.<br>
